node.text:
Our friends at Sequoia Parks Conservative have set up a recovery fund to help with efforts from their current wildfire. Please donate at the link @sequoiaparksconservancy 
•••••
You have been asking how you can help. 

Announcing the KNP Complex Fire Recovery Fund for Sequoia National Park. 

In the evening of September 9, 2021, a lightning storm came through Sequoia National Park. Fire erupted and national park firefighters responded to local ignitions. By September 14, there was a mandatory evacuation of Ash Mountain, Lodgepole, Wuksachi Lodge, and Three Rivers, CA. 

Donations to the KNP Complex Fire Recovery Fund for Sequoia National Park will fund efforts to rebuild trails, protect sequoia groves and meadows, safeguard cultural and historic features, reestablish access to Crystal Cave, restore wildlife habitat, and more. 

Thank you for everything you do. 

📷: Hunter Tidd

node.text:
Small parks can be explosive with adventures and history. #smallparksaturday Give our friends Camp Nelson National Monument @campnelsonnps a follow as they get their start on IG. We know they will be sharing great stories & history. 
——
Thanks to @campnelsonnps for sharing with us all. 
•
“Camp Nelson was the rendezvous of soldiery and birthplace of liberty to Kentucky. It is hallowed in the minds of thousands.” 
-Reverend John G. Fee, 1877

Initially established in 1863 as a Federal supply depot and hospital, Camp Nelson evolved over the course of the Civil War. Situated in a slave holding state where the Emancipation Proclamation didn’t apply, the site became a beacon for enslaved people seeking freedom, protection, and employment. The supply depot soon became a recruiting camp for soldiers who would become United States Colored Troops and served as a refugee camp for their wives and children. 

At the height of its use in 1865, Camp Nelson encompassed roughly 4,000 acres. The camp included more than 300 buildings and tents that served as a quartermaster, commissary depot, ordnance depot, recruitment center, prison, a hospital, and more. Positioned between Hickman Creek and the Kentucky River, eight earthen forts or batteries, primarily constructed by impressed enslaved labor along its northern perimeter helped to protect the camp. The camp remained an active U.S. Army installation until June 1866. 

Today, Camp Nelson National Monument, administered by the National Park Service, protects the core historic Civil War-era site. It interprets the complicated and sometimes tragic stories associated with the nation’s struggle for realized Emancipation. Located 20 miles south of Lexington, Kentucky the park includes the main encampment area and the Fee Memorial Church on the site of the Home for Colored Refugees. 

Currently, the park’s Visitor Center is open Wednesday-Sunday, 9am-5pm.

Sequoia National Park is currently closed due to wildfires. These fires got started last week with lightning strikes. Please stay up to date from @sequoiakingsnps 
•••••
All the best to @sequoiakingsnps
@sequoiaparksconservancy and the fire personnel for a quick containment. God speed. 
•
Sequoia National Park is closed, and all employees that live inside of park boundaries have been evacuated due to growth of the KNP Complex. Here, firefighters assigned to the complex prepare the historic Sequoia entrance sign for the possibility of fire in the area by wrapping it with aluminum-based burn-resistant material. 

EVACUATIONS UPDATE

The evacuation WARNING (not order) has been expanded to encompass the rest of Three Rivers, from Edison Drive east to Mineral King Road. This includes the Cherokee Oaks, North Fork Drive, South Fork Drive, Old Three Rivers Road, and Blossom Drive. 
Mineral King Road and Highway 198 east of the intersection with Mineral King Road is under evacuation order.

node.text:
Flowing into this week’s #waterfallwednesday is this beauty from Acadia NP. With the leaves changing soon, Acadia will glow with her Autumn colors soon. 
••••
Many thanks to John  @jkputnamphoto for sharing the Acadia goodness. 
•
Nicolas Cage gets a bad rep. I’ve long wanted to see Leaving Las Vegas and last night I finally sat down and watched it. It’s haunting… and he is the ghost. And nothing against Elisabeth Shue, she plays an equally tough roll. I’m still trying to figure out out who the antagonist in the film is. One might argue that they’re each their own antagonist… but I don’t think that true, they’re both equally accepting of themselves and each other. Such a beautiful and dangerous concept. Anyway, I highly recommend sitting down with the whole family and giving it a watch… NO, I’m kidding! DONT WATCH THIS WITH KIDS! Unless they’re grown up in which case it will just be super awkward and uncomfortable. Also, if you like this image and want to see more from the same morning head over to Twitter and find me at jkputnamphoto!

node.text:
O Say Can You See….

On this day, September 14, 1814 the British bombed Fort McHenry @fortmchenrynps in Baltimore, MD. Francis Scott Key witnessed the flag still flying and wrote what would become our National Anthem. Long my she wave. 

As the first park we experience growing up, Fort McHenry will always hold a special place in our heart with rich stories and history. 
••••
Thanks to the NPS @nationalparkservice for telling America’s stories and for protecting places wild. 
•
“By the Dawn's Early Light..." 🇺🇸⁣
⁣
On September 14, 1814, Francis Scott Key penned a poem which was later set to music and in 1931 became America’s national anthem, “The Star-Spangled Banner.” The poem, originally titled “The Defence of Fort M'Henry,” was written after Key witnessed the Maryland fort being bombarded by the British during the War of 1812. Following a 25-hour bombardment, onlookers glimpsed the huge 30x42-foot American flag flying over the fort, signaling that Fort McHenry had held.⁣
⁣
In 1933, @fortmchenrynps became an area administered by the National Park Service. Today, visitors to the fort can explore exhibits, participate in programs, and tour restored barracks. ⁣
⁣
Image: Three park rangers raise the large 15-star garrison flag inside #FortMcHenry. ⁣
⁣
